<head>
<title>To Perform Screening Program</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>To Perform Screening Program</h1>
<ol>
<li>Choose the Start New Screening Program option.</li>
<li>Select the Water Body.</li>
<li>Select the sampling location on the map.</li>
<li>View the sampling frequencies.  Any Parameters which need sampling are then added to the program.<br>
This is repeated for all Samplers for the Water Body.</li>
<li>Click the submit button to submit the program.<br>
An email will automatically be sent to the Contractors assigned to each Sampler, <br>
requesting them to take a Sample and listing with Parameters to be analysed.<br>
The Contractors take Samples and send them to the Laboratory assigned to each Sampler, along with Parameter details. <br>
The Contractor updates the System so that it knows a Sample has been sent. <br>
The Laboratories analyse the Samples and bulk upload the results.<br>
When all Samples have been analysed, an email is sent automatically to you, advising you that the Screening Program has been completed.</li>
</ol>
<a href="HelpPage.html">Return to Help Page</a>
</body>


<head>
<title>To Schedule Sampling Frequencies</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>To Schedule Sampling Frequencies</h1>
<ol>
<li>Choose the Schedule of Sampling Frequencies option.</li>
<li>Select the Water Body and then choose to group the data either by<br>
Sampler/Frequency/Screening Parameter or by <br>
Sampler/Screening Parameter. A list of screening frequencies is then displayed.</li>
</ol>
<a href="HelpPage.html">Return to Help Page</a>
</body>


<head>
<title>To Create Environmental Audit Report</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>To Create Environmental Audit Report</h1>
<ol>
<li>Choose the Create Environmental Audit Report option. <br>
A report is generated containing a table of Sample records with all parameter values <br>
grouped by Water Body and Sampler, sorted by date.</li>
<li>Select the Water Body and select parameters analysed at that body. <br>
A graph will be shown with these parameter and a horizontal line representing the <br>
exceedances applicable to each parameter.</li>
<li>Select an exceedance line and information about that exceedance will be displayed <br>
(which parameter it applies to its value.) Where a detection limit has been recorded, <br>
rather than an actual value, this will be highlighted on the report.</li>
</ol>
<a href="HelpPage.html">Return to Help Page</a>
</body>


<head>
<title>To Create Exceedance Report</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>To Create Exceedance Report</h1>
<ol>
<li>Choose the Create Exceedance Report option.</li>
<li>Select the Sampler location from a map. <br>
The report consists of a table showing only those Samples where an exceedance was recorded for a parameter. <br>
The records will be in date order (most recent first), and will contain date, parameter whose value was exceeded, <br>
the parameter value, the exceedance and the magnitude of exceedance. Where a detection limit has been recorded,<br>
rather than an actual value, this will be highlighted on the report.</li>
</ol>
<a href="HelpPage.html">Return to Help Page</a>
</body>


<head>
<title>Glossary</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Glossary</h1>
<table border="1">
<tr>
<th>Term</th>
<th>Definition</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Map</td>
<td>A visual representation of the mine site in the form of an aerial photo.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Sampler</td>
<td>A generic term for an observation station that is set up at a specific sampling location to allow samples to be taken.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Sampling location</td>
<td>A geographical position at the Tiffany Gold Mine defined by a latitude/longitude pair and represented by a marker on a map <br>
at which a water sample is taken at a prescribed frequency.  Samples can be taken above ground (creek, domestic water tank) 
and below ground (bore). </td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>(Environmental)parameter</td>
<td>A numerical description of an observed property of the environment such as pH or EC.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Screening Frequency</td>
<td>The period of time between sampling events which may vary from sampler to sampler and from parameter to parameter.<br>
Frequencies are divided into screening frequency (only some parameters are analysed)and comprehensive screening frequency <br>
(all parameters are analysed.)The latter always occurs less often. </td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Screening Program</td>
<td>An activity in which many pre-defined sampling locations are visited to retrieve samples that have to be analysed for a set of parameters at that time. </td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Sampling Date</td>
<td>Date at which a water sample is taken for later analysis in a laboratory.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>EC</td>
<td>Electrical conductivity measured in micro Siemens per centimetre (uS/cm, one of the many environmental parameters measure in a water sample indicaive of salinity.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>.klm</td>
<td>KLM is a file format used to display geographical data in an Earth browser such as Google Earth, Google Maps.</td>
</tr>
</table>
<a href="HelpPage.html">Return to Help Page</a>
</body>

<head>
<title>Definitions</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Definitions</h1>
<h4>Water Body:</h4>
<p>The information of water body can be divided into two groups, ground water and surface water.  <br> 
Ground water is contained in aquifers; each aquifies may have different exceeding minimum and/or maximum limits for all parameters are monitored. <br>
Surface water bodies are creeks and rivers which also have their own exceeding minimum and/or maximum limits for monitoring. </p>
<h4>Sampler:</h4>
<p>The water samplers are identified by their alphanumeric tag(eg GW123)and have a geographical <br>
position that should be reflected on a map with the option to enter the latitude and longitude either from the keyboard or .klm files.  <br>
Samplers need to be assigned to the water body contractors monitored.</p>
<p>Ground water samplers have a licence number (eg 20BL845484)and a monitoring purpose description.  Ground water samplers also have: </p>
<ol>
<li>A screening frequency at which a defined subset of parameters is screened.</li>
<li>A comprehensive screening frequency at which time the water depth to collar is measured to calculate </li>
<li> Ground water level above sea level</li>
</ol>
<p>Surface water samplers are carrying a monitoring description and the same screening frequency <br>
information as the ground water except the depth of river or creek that the sample is taken from.  The parameters measured for ground and surface water are <br>
shown in the table below: </p>
<table border ="1">
<caption>Parameters of Ground Water and Surface Water</caption>
<tr>
<td>&nbsp;</td>
<td>Ground Water</td>
<td>Surface Water</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>PH</td>
<td>O</td>
<td>O</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>EC [uS/cm]</td>
<td>O</td>
<td>O</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Temperature[ C]</td>
<td>O</td>
<td>O</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Depth to collar [m]</td>
<td>O</td>
<td>X</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Fluoride [mg/L]</td>
<td>X</td>
<td>O</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Chromium [mg/L]</td>
<td>X</td>
<td>O</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Arsenic [mg/L]</td>
<td>O</td>
<td>O</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Oil</td>
<td>O</td>
<td>O</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Grease [ppm]</td>
<td>O</td>
<td>O</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The screening frequencies are: daily, weekly, fortnightly, monthly, half yearly and yearly.</p>
<h4>Reports and Graphs</h4> 
<p>The system generates reports and graphs.  The reports are divided into two parts audit reports and exceeding <br>
value reports.  The audit reports contain a table of parameter values (column heading)collected at all dates (row heading)
grouped by sampling points for a selectable water body.  The graphs included for <br>
each water body sampler for a selectable list of parameters.  The graphs contain a horizontal line for each of the exceeding applicable to the selected parameters which are also <br>
selectable.  The exceeding value reports consist of a table generated by selecting a sampler from a map and containing the parameters, date and measured values together <br> 
with the exceedance values and the magnitude of exceedance values. <br>
All detection limits are marked as such and not presented as measured values.</p>
